## ğŸš€ Pipeline Stages

### âœ… Build
- Installs dependencies using `npm install`

### âœ… Test
- Runs basic or placeholder test (`echo "Running tests..."`)

### âœ… Deploy
- Starts the app using `node server.js` or runs it via Docker (optional)

---

## ğŸ“¦ Jenkinsfile

```groovy
pipeline {
    agent any

    stages {
        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                echo 'Installing dependencies...'
                sh 'npm install'
            }
        }

        stage('Test') {
            steps {
                echo 'Running tests...'
                sh 'echo "Tests passed!"'
            }
        }

        stage('Deploy') {
            steps {
                echo 'Deploying application...'
                sh 'nohup node server.js &'
            }
        }
    }
}
ğŸ” Auto Trigger Setup
The pipeline automatically runs when you push code to GitHub using a webhook.

GitHub Webhook Configuration:
Start Jenkins on your VM at http://localhost:8080

Expose Jenkins to the internet using Ngrok:

ngrok http 8080
Copy the forwarding URL (e.g., https://abc123.ngrok.io)

Go to your GitHub repo â†’ Settings â†’ Webhooks â†’ Add webhook

Payload URL: https://<ngrok-url>/github-webhook/

Content type: application/json

Events: Just the push event

Save webhook. It should now trigger Jenkins on each commit.

ğŸ§ª How to Test the Pipeline
Make changes in any file (e.g., server.js)

Commit and push to GitHub:

git add .
git commit -m "Test pipeline trigger"
git push
Check the Jenkins dashboard for auto-triggered build status.

